Extracts and analyzes the Secure Boot Platform Key (PK) certificate from UEFI firmware, displaying certificate subject and thumbprint information for validation and auditing purposes.

Detailed Description

This PowerShell script performs a read-only inspection of the UEFI Secure Boot Platform Key (PK) by:

Querying the system's Secure Boot Platform Key using:
Get-SecureBootUEFI -Name PK
Verifying that a Platform Key exists and contains data.
Searching the PK binary data for an embedded X.509 certificate using ASN.1 DER certificate markers.
Extracting the certificate payload from the Secure Boot variable.
Writing the extracted certificate to a temporary .cer file.
Loading the certificate into the .NET X509 certificate provider.
Displaying key certificate metadata:
Subject
Thumbprint
Reporting extraction or parsing failures when certificate data cannot be identified.
What It Verifies
Presence of a Secure Boot Platform Key (PK)
Accessibility of UEFI Secure Boot variables
Embedded X.509 certificate availability
Certificate ownership information
Platform Key thumbprint for inventory and comparison




$pk = Get-SecureBootUEFI -Name PK

if (-not $pk) {
    Write-Output "No PK found"
    exit 1
}

$bytes = $pk.Bytes

if (-not $bytes) {
    Write-Output "PK has no byte data"
    exit 1
}

# Look for embedded certificate using ASN.1 marker
$certStart = -1
for ($i=0; $i -lt $bytes.Length-4; $i++) {
    if ($bytes[$i] -eq 0x30 -and $bytes[$i+1] -eq 0x82) {
        $certStart = $i
        break
    }
}

if ($certStart -lt 0) {
    Write-Output "No certificate header found in PK (non-standard format)"
    exit 2
}

# Extract cert
$certBytes = $bytes[$certStart..($bytes.Length-1)]

# Ensure path exists
$path = "C:\Windows\Temp\pk_cert.cer"
[System.IO.File]::WriteAllBytes($path, $certBytes)

try {
    $cert = New-Object System.Security.Cryptography.X509Certificates.X509Certificate2($path)
    $cert | Select Subject, Thumbprint | Format-List
}
catch {
    Write-Output "Failed to parse certificate"
}

